\chapter<<2162>>Methodology<<2162>>
\label<<2163>>cha:methodology<<2163>>
\begin<<2164>>quote<<2164>>
To iterate is human, to recurse divine. --- L. Peter Deutsch
\end<<2165>>quote<<2165>>
In this chapter, a high-level overview of PyPedal<<2166>><<2166>> is provided, giving
the reader the definitions of the key components of the system. This section
defines the concepts used by the remaining sections.
\section<<2167>>Reordering and Renumbering<<2167>>\label<<2168>>sec:methodology-reordering-and-renumbering<<2168>>\index<<2169>>reordering and renumbering<<2169>>
Many computations on pedigrees require that the pedigree be renumbered such that animal IDs are consecutive from 1 to \character<<2170>>n<<2170>>, where \character<<2171>>n<<2171>> is the total number of animals in the pedigree. By default, all pedigrees are renumbered at load time. If you pedigree is already renumbered and you do not want it renumbered again you must set the \begin<<2468>>tex2html_deferred<<2468>>\samp<<2172>>renumber<<2172>>\end<<2469>>tex2html_deferred<<2469>> option to 0. The renumbering process requires that the pedigree be reordered such that parents always precede their offspring in the list of animal IDs. The actual ID assigned to an animal is of no particular importance, and it is even possible for parents to have larger IDs than their offspring.  PyPedal<<2173>><<2173>> can reorder any pedigree unless there is an error in it that would prevent unambiguously placing parents before offspring.  For example, a pedigree containing a keypunch error such that an animal is one of its own grandparents cannot be reordered because there is no way to unambiguously order the animals.  The \module<<2174>>pyp_utils<<2174>> module provides two routines for pedigree reordering, \function<<2175>>reorder()<<2175>> and \function<<2176>>fast\_reorder()<<2176>>.  By default, \function<<2177>>reorder()<<2177>> is used to reorder pedigrees in place.  It does this by maintaining a list of animal IDs that have been processed; whenever a parent that is not in the  list of encountered animals the offspring of that parent are moved to the end of the pedigree.  This ensures the pedigree is properly sorted such that all parents precede their offspring. Founders are also grouped together at the beginning of the pedigree. This procedure will always correctly reorder a pedigree but it can be quite inefficient as it is similar to an insertion sort, which has a worst-case runtime proportional to \begin<<2376>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<2376>>$n^<<2178>>2<<2178>>$\end<<2377>>tex2html_wrap_inline<<2377>>\space \cite<<2179>>Cormen2003<<2179>>.
\begin<<2470>>tex2html_deferred<<2470>>\par\end<<2471>>tex2html_deferred<<2471>>
\function<<2180>>fast\_reorder()<<2180>> provides a much faster means of reordering a pedigree, but can incorrectly reorder a pedigree in some cases.  When an instance of a \class<<2181>>NewAnimal<<2181>> object is created the \method<<2182>>pad_id()<<2182>> method is called.  \method<<2183>>pad_id()<<2183>> uses the animal ID and birth year to form an ID used by \function<<2184>>by pyp_utils/fast_reorder()<<2184>> for quick sorting; if your pedigree file is numbered such that offspring always have larger IDs than their parents and your birth years (if provided) are correct (that is, parents always born BEFORE offspring) then \function<<2185>>pyp_utils.fast_reorder()<<2185>> works as expected.  If you do not provide birth years in your pedigree file but your parent IDs are always smaller than your animal IDs, the reordering will be correct.  If you do not provide birth years, all animals in the pedigree will be assigned a default value of `1900'.  In that case, if parents have IDs larger than that of one or more of their offspring, the pedigree will be incorrectly reordered by \function<<2186>>fast\_reorder()<<2186>>.  If your pedigree file contains birth years, or you know that parents always have smaller IDs than their offspring, then \function<<2187>>fast\_reorder()<<2187>> will correctly reorder your pedigree in linear time. Founders
are not guaranteed to be grouped at the beginning of the pedigree when \function<<2188>>fast\_reorder()<<2188>> is used; if you are going to calculate coefficients of
partial inbreeding (Section \ref<<2189>>sec:methodology-partial-inbreeding<<2189>>) then you should instead use \function<<2190>>reorder()<<2190>> to reorder your pedigree.
\begin<<2472>>tex2html_deferred<<2472>>\par\end<<2473>>tex2html_deferred<<2473>>
The performance difference between the two reordering routines is not very noticeable on pedigrees of a few hundred to a few thousand animals, but is quite dramatic for very large pedigrees. If your pedigree file is already reordered then there is essentially no performance difference between the two. When creating a pedigree file from data stored in a relational database, let the database perform the sort for you by using an \begin<<2474>>tex2html_deferred<<2474>>\samp<<2191>>ORDER BY<<2191>>\end<<2475>>tex2html_deferred<<2475>> statement.
\begin<<2476>>tex2html_deferred<<2476>>\par\end<<2477>>tex2html_deferred<<2477>>
\section<<2192>>Animal Identification and Cross-References<<2192>>
\label<<2193>>sec:methodology-id-mapping<<2193>>
\index<<2194>>ID mapping<<2194>>
There are a number of identification attributes associated with animal objects in PyPedal<<2195>><<2195>> pedigrees. A description of those fields, as well as their default values, is provided in Table \ref<<2196>>tbl:objects-animal-objects-new-animal-attributes<<2196>>. This section describes the data structures provided for mapping between various animal IDs. Table \ref<<2197>>tbl:methodology-id-mapping<<2197>> lists the four structures provided for ID mapping and lists the default values for pedigrees with integral (\texttt<<2198>>asd<<2198>> formats) and string (\texttt<<2199>>ASD<<2199>> formats) IDs. Renumbered PyPedal<<2200>><<2200>> pedigree objects store animal objects in a list that is typically indexed by renumbered ID. When animal IDs are strings (see \ref<<2201>>sec:pedigree-format-codes<<2201>>) they are hashed to an integer and the original ID is stored in a name field. In renumbered pedigrees the original ID is stored and replaced by a renumbered ID.
\begin<<2478>>tex2html_deferred<<2478>>\par\end<<2479>>tex2html_deferred<<2479>>
Once your pedigree is renumbered it is quite easy to see how these maps can be used to convert between various IDs. The maps mean that you don't have to worry about renumbered IDs and can continue to think about your animals in terms of their original IDs, whether they be ID numbers or names. Consider the Newfoundland pedigree presented in Figure \ref<<2202>>fig:newfoundland-colored-pedigree<<2202>> -- it is much more convenient to think about the dog named Kaptn Kvols von Widdersdorf, rather than the dog whose name was hashed to the ID 5523557808241831142 amd renumbered to 48. For example, suppose you wanted to determine his coefficient of inbreeding. It is simple to do using the maps:
\begin<<2203>>tex2html_preform<<2203>><tex2html_verbatim_mark>verbatim154#\end<<2204>>tex2html_preform<<2204>>
\texttt<<2205>>example.namemap['Kaptn Kvols von Widdersdorf']<<2205>> returns the original ID assigned to the name, while \texttt<<2206>>example.idmap[...]<<2206>> converts from the original ID to the renumbered ID. This sort of ID/name mapping is sued in a number of places in PyPedal<<2207>><<2207>>, such as in the three generation pedigree routine in the \module<<2208>>pyp\_reports<<2208>> module.
\begin<<2480>>tex2html_deferred<<2480>>\par\end<<2481>>tex2html_deferred<<2481>>
Note that if an animal has its original ID as its name, which is the default when integral IDs and no animal names are provided, the name is changed to the renumbered ID when the pedigree is renumbered.
\begin<<2209>>center<<2209>>
    \tablecaption<<2210>>Animal identification and cross-references.<<2210>>
